1. d4 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. c4 g6 { Hello everyone and thank you for purchasing my course on the Grünfeld, designed for players who are new to the Grünfeld as well as those who have been playing the opening for some time but now wish to do a deeper study of it.

The Grünfeld is one of the most challenging but in my view also one of the most rewarding openings in chess. It was the first opening I ever learned, and it is one that I will always think about very fondly. Not only did it teach me theory, but it also taught me a lot about many essential elements of the game of chess.

From the get-go we focus on an early development of our kingside, letting our opponents build up a commanding pawn mass in the center. But then, just before they can establish an iron grip, we break in the center with ...d5 and the fight begins!

The Grünfeld is an opening for the keen tactician since we counter White's static advantage (namely, their better control of the center) with the use of our lead in development . Along the way, we build our skills in dynamic positions where strong handling of the initiative is often the key to success. The opening's tricky waters help us to hone our eye for tactical combinations as well as strengthen our calculation abilities, as one early mistake can be just as costly for us as for our opponents.

However, the Grünfeld player's hunting ground extends beyond the pretty combinations of the early opening stage. While White may often be left with an imposing pawn center, that comes at the cost of leaving us with a pawn majority on the queenside. This imbalance makes the opening and middle game tricky for Black, but it can make many endgames treacherous for our opponents as our queenside pawn majority finally comes to life. Many games will be won by us by advancing the a- and b-pawns in the later stages of the game, and this imbalance combined with the forcing nature of the opening molds Grünfeld players into great practical endgame players over time.

Many White players fear the experienced Grünfeld player because of their reputation for sharp players who revel in the tactical chaos that often arises on the board. But it is my view that Grünfeld veterans are just as dangerous in the later stages of the game as this is an opening where you can amass a lot of experience in a range of thematic endgames. This course embraces this aspect of the opening - we will often find ourselves willingly entering simplified middle game positions with the goal of outplaying our opponents later on in the game.

About the philosophy of the course in general: we will address all of the major possibilities available to White and aim to strike a balance between safe and solid play. If our opponents play well, we will focus on avoiding problematic positions. At the same time, we will seize upon any mistakes our opponents make in order to grab the advantage early on if allowed. The recommendations in the repertoire are a fusion of what I consider to be the objectively best play for Black in the current state of Grünfeld theory, while also acknowledging that any selection of lines by an author is going to be heavily influenced by their particular playing style. Thus, when it comes to style, a short description is in order.

My approach has always been to play logical and straightforward chess without too much speculative risk. I like to embrace all the different stages of the game and find the beauty of winning a technically tricky endgame to be on par with a victory that comes from a sharp tactical sequence. At the same time, since chess is a game of decisions, I believe that it’s always a good idea to put your opponents to difficult decisions wherever possible. I am sure that my approach to chess has had a big impact on this course. As such, the student can expect a mixture of tactically sharp lines, positional and endgame themes, as well as a repertoire where we seek out lines where it’s easy for our opponents to go wrong. I hope that you will find this approach both engaging and helpful to your own chess.

A couple of final comments:

The course itself is quite challenging, with almost 30 hours of video content and close to 400 trainable variations. I have tried to keep the most challenging theory to a minimum, in order to make it accessible to players of a broad skill level.. However, I believe it’s a dangerous habit to enter an inferior position simply to avoid theory, and so I have only opted for less studied or less demanding lines in those instances where I felt we would not be making any sacrifices regarding the objective merits of our repertoire. The result, I hope, is a relatively compact repertoire that is at the same time robust enough that it can be wielded against opponents of any and all strengths.

The study of this course will give you a very solid framework upon which to further deepen your knowledge. At times in the course I will stop at a certain position and suggest further individual analysis, often recommending either to play a sparring match from certain positions with a training partner or to simply analyze the position further with the use of a chess engine. This is of course completely optional, but may be a helpful practice should you wish to develop a deeper understanding of certain positions that will be covered.

That is it from me for the introduction, and I will see you in the course forum should you have any further questions or doubts.

Best of luck in your Grünfeld journey, and I hope that you will have a lot of fun and enjoy exciting games with this opening for many years to come! } 
*

