3. f3 Nc6!? {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This line is commonly referred to as the Anti-Grünfeld and presents us with a wide choice of how to respond. Moves such as } 3...c5 { in the style of the Benoni, } ) ( 3...Bg7 { transposing to the King's Indian Defense, or the classical response of } ) ( 3...d5 { are perfectly reasonable.

The latter is of course the move that most captures the spirit of Grünfeld's play, and as such was my intended first recommendation. However, as I dove deeper into the state of theory in this line in 2022 I realized that the amount of must-know information borders on unmanageable.

Additionally, the lines are not easy for humans to remember as much of it is very sharp computer-generated play. Therefore, I have decided to propose an alternative way of playing. } ) { The idea behind this move is that Black will target White along the dark squares.

This is a sound concept against the 3.f3 Anti-Grünfeld because one drawback of placing the pawn on f3 is that the dark squares are slightly weakened. With our last move, we are already threatening 4...e5.

This provocative move has been favored by the young Russian Grandmaster Vladislav Artemiev with compelling results against strong opposition. Magnus Carlsen himself has played this move, obtaining a draw against Levon Aronian in the 2019 London Classic. } 
4. d5 Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c4][%csl Gc4]} 
5. e4 {[%cal Gf1c4]} { White has more space, but at the same time there is a risk of becoming overextended.

Black's approach in this position is to use the edge in development to undermine White's center. White on the other hand wants to consolidate the space advantage and squeeze Black in the long run. } d6 
6. Nc3 ( { Black frees up the d7-square in case White plays } 6.f4 { . } ) Bg7 
7. f4 { This is in my view the clearly best move. White grabs the center and forces us to retreat to a more passive square. } Ned7 
8. Nh3 { This top move has been chosen by the world's best players with White, including Ding Liren and Magnus Carlsen.

The idea is that the knight will reroute to f2, from where it will lend support to White's central e4-pawn. It will also cover the g4-square (thus killing off ...Ng4 ideas) as well as cover the g1-a7 diagonal.

This latter point can be relevant as after White castles, there will not be ...Qb6+ ideas after Black moves their c-pawn. } Nb6 { Black postpones castling to accelerate placing pressure on White's center. } 
9. Nf2 e6 
10. Be2 exd5 
11. cxd5 { Any other way of capturing would damage the integrity of White's pawn center and cost White their advantage. } O-O 
12. O-O c6 { Black continues to break down White's center. } 
13. dxc6 { White almost always grabs the pawn to avoid 13...cxd5 and keep their central structure as compact as possible. } bxc6 
14. Bf3 { This was tried in one game by the top Polish Grandmaster Jan-Krzysztof Duda. } Rb8 { Black steps the rook onto the semi-open file and away from the h1-a8 diagonal where White's bishop on } { f3 may cause us trouble. For now we avoid the move { 14...d5 since White would play 15.e5 kicking our knight back to a passive square. } 
15. Qc2 d5 
16. Rd1 ( { Now is a good time to break in the centre since if White plays } 16.e5 { we can now develop with tempo with the strong in-between move of } 16...Bf5 { , hitting the queen. After } 17.Qd1 { we would then play } 17...Nfd7 { with good coordination. } ) Re8 
17.-- ( { Black has great pressure against White's center. If White tries to just sit on their position with a waiting move like } 17.h3 { , we can play } 17...Bd7 { next when we are now ready to capture on } { e4 . If White then plays 18.e5 we will have 18...Bf5 winning time against White's queen on c2 .

White can keep the balance with some difficult-to-find moves such as 17.b3 or 17.Ne2 .

However, natural-looking moves such as 17.Be3 (met by 17...Nc4 ) or @@StartFEN@@1rbqr1k1/p4pbp/1np2np1/3p4/4PP2/2N2B2/PPQ2NPP/R1BR2K1 w - - 2 17@@EndFEN@@ 17.e5 (met by 17...Bf5 ) leads to a big advantage for Black. } { 16...Qe7 was played in Duda-Delchev (2020) but it is slightly inaccurate. After 17.e5 White suddenly has a slight edge as Black's pieces got pushed back. } )
