7. Be3 ( { In his Lifetime Repertoires course on the Grünfeld, Peter Svidler remarked that } 7.Be3 { is a move that he has never enjoyed facing, and I think many Grünfeld players will sympathize with this point of view. The reason is that it can be extremely hard to generate winning chances against the 7.Be3 systems, as White’s setup after 8.Qd2 is simply extremely solid!

Here we will be studying a plan involving a quick exchange of the queens and then seeking active piece play along the open c-file in order to neutralize White’s central pawn advantage. Oftentimes White will be left with the king in the center of the board after the exchange of queens. This means that as Black we should be careful to avoid certain positions where White’s king activity may become uncomfortable for us. With the best play, Black can expect to equalize against all of White’s different tries in this variation. } ) c5 
