1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 
4. cxd5 ( { This move marks the beginning of the Exchange Variation.

The study of the Grünfeld can be broadly divided into two sections. The first part is when White maintains the tension in the center. The second part is when White plays } 4.cxd5 { entering the so-called Exchange Variation. This is the most popular move and leads to many challenging variations. Traditionally, it has been seen as the most ambitious approach that White can take against the Grünfeld.

Strategically speaking, the Exchange Variation is premised on the idea that White's best bet is to establish an imposing center as quickly as possible. Black has to play } 4...Nxd5 { here and White's idea is to follow up with } 5.e4 { . } ) Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { This is the most popular of White's seventh move options. White is choosing to develop the bishop first in order to follow up with 8.Ne2.

By avoiding placing the king's knight on f3, White stops Black from any problematic pinning of the knight (and consequent undermining of the center) that often happens after Black plays the light-squared bishop to g4. } c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 
8. Ne2 O-O ( { By castling first, we avoid some complicated lines after } 8...Nc6 9.d5!? ) 
9. Be3 Nc6 
10. O-O b6 ( { This move has quickly established itself as the weapon of choice among elite Grünfeld players in 2022. Black has tried many alternatives over the years, notably } 10...Qc7 { and } ) ( 10...Bg4 { . The latter is Peter Svidler's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire course.

Of course, all of the main moves are playable, but I am attracted to the simplicity of this calm developing move, seeking to place our light-squared bishop on the long h1-a8 diagonal in order to complete our minor piece development. } ) 
11. dxc5 { White does sometimes grab the pawn, but Black is well prepared to face this possibility as we will secure a lot of lines of attack which will offer full compensation. } Qc7 
12. cxb6 { Taking the pawn should be welcomed by us, as it will immediately give Black a semi-open c-file and a-file to use to pressure White dynamically. It is a rare guest in Grandmaster play for good reason, Black receives too much active play for the pawn. } axb6 
13. Rb1 Ne5 
14. Bd5 Rb8 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gc8a6]} { We have a typical Grünfeld middlegame where our pawn deficit is compensated by our well-placed pieces and structural superiority. We will soon kick out White's bishop by pushing our pawn to e6, while our own light-squared bishop can land on a6.

These positions are uncomfortable for White because Black has many easy targets (both pieces and pawns) to pressure. Objectively speaking the position is equal, but in tournament practice, Black has scored greater than 50%. } 
