2. c4 g6 { Our study of the Grünfeld begins after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 , when here White’s most common continuation is 3.Nc3 .

To begin the course, however, we will be investigating some less common possibilities. These are 3.d5 , 3.Bg5 , and 3.h4 . Even though some moves may be rare, that does not mean that we should not take them seriously! However, in this chapter, we will show how to obtain equality (or even an advantage!) with precise play against these systems, by trying to exploit the drawbacks of such possibilities.

For example, against 3.d5 we will seek to profit from White’s overextension in the center by chipping away at this pawn. At the same time, since White is spending time with this move we may be able to exploit their king if it stays in the center for too long! Against 3.Bg5 we will once again look to exploit White’s early aggressive play, by jumping into the center with 3...Ne4 and asking an uncomfortable question to our opponents - where should they go with their bishop?! Against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@ 3.h4 , we will try to show that White needed to be more patient with the kingside offensive. } 
