2. c4 g6 
3. f3 Nc6!? ( { This line is commonly referred to as the Anti-Grünfeld and presents us with a wide choice of how to respond. Moves such as } 3...c5 { in the style of the Benoni, } ) ( 3...Bg7 { transposing to the King's Indian Defense, or the classical response of } ) ( 3...d5 { are perfectly reasonable.

The latter is of course the move that most captures the spirit of Grünfeld's play, and as such was my intended first recommendation. However, as I dove deeper into the state of theory in this line in 2022 I realized that the amount of must-know information borders on unmanageable.

Additionally, the lines are not easy for humans to remember as much of it is very sharp computer-generated play. Therefore, I have decided to propose an alternative way of playing. } ) { The idea behind this move is that Black will target White along the dark squares.

This is a sound concept against the 3.f3 Anti-Grünfeld because one drawback of placing the pawn on f3 is that the dark squares are slightly weakened. With our last move, we are already threatening 4...e5.

