[White "8) 4.Nf3 - Rare Fifth Moves"]
[Black "Chapter 8) 4.Nf3 - Rare Fifth Moves"]
[Date "2023.02.07"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D90"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23142000"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 
4. Nf3 Bg7 { One of White’s most popular continuations against the Grünfeld is the flexible fourth move of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 . We will continue with 4...Bg7 and here we will examine several continuations. Two of the most trendy and challenging are the pawn moves of 5.h3 and 5.h4 .

The idea of the former is to take away the g4-square from Black. As a result, the typical idea of playing ...Bg4 (pinning White’s knight on f3 and thus undermining the d4-pawn) is no longer possible.

In the course, we will show a strong alternative plan for Black involving a fianchetto of the light-squared bishop followed by an early queen trade. This variation is instructive as the idea of exchanging queens (and often a set of minor pieces) in order to ease the constraints imposed on Black by White’s strong pawn center is very typical in the Grünfeld.

In the case of 5.h4 we will continue with a rare idea in the form of 7...Bg4!? [/variation/21987480/#/7/b] which will force White to find a very narrow path to keep any advantage. In the main line, we also see the move 11...c5 [/variation/21987484/#/11/b] being played, again seeking to counter-attack in the center in order to defuse White’s fast kingside attack. } 
