1. d4 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 
4. Nf3 Bg7 
5. Bg5 -- ( { This is a popular variation but in my view, it is not so challenging because after } 5...Ne4 6.cxd5 { we get to play } 6...Nxg5 { , winning White’s dark-squared bishop. That said, it’s important to be ready for the ensuing pawn structure since this is one of the few variations where the central pawn structure ends up being quite inflexible.

White will be left with pawns on e3 and d4, while Black will be left with pawns on d5 and c6. This is the so-called Carlsbad structure, one of the most important pawn structures in chess (most often seen via the Queen’s Gambit Declined) .

Objectively the position is comfortable for Black but it does lead to slower more positional play than Grünfeld players are accustomed to, so we should make sure to be familiar with the typical positional maneuvers that this structure gives rise to. } )
