This is a common phenomenon when one side has a space advantage in the center as the other side has less choice of good squares. } 
12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 
13. Kxd2 { This is an important endgame, and we should study how to play it well as the truth is that White's play is easier from a practical point of view owing to the space advantage. However, with precise play we can prove equality. } Nc6 { In a perfect world, we would love to be able to play 14...Rd8 and 15...e5, breaking down White's center. However, White will not give us such an easy time of it and will be applying pressure along the b- and c-files. } 
14. Rhc1 Rd8 {[%mdl 32768]} 
15. Rc5 { Sometimes White plays in this fashion in order to prevent us from achieving the pawn break with e5. This is a tricky move to meet as White tries to suffocate us using their space advantage. } Bf5 {[%cal Gf5b1,Ra1b1][%csl Rb1]} { Cutting out 16.Rb1 ideas. } 
16. Rac1 Be4 {[%cal Ge4g2,Ge4d5,Gd5a2][%csl Rg2,Rf3,Ra2]} { This is a nice multi-purpose move. Black pressures f3 and g2, and at the same time may reroute the bishop to d5 to attack the White a-pawn in some situations. This would also cut off the c5-rook from the protection of the e5-square. } 
17. Bd3 { This was Kramnik's choice against Fabiano Caruana. } Bxd3 
18. Kxd3 e5! { This move solves Black's problems. } 
19. Nxe5 Nxe5+ 
20. Bxe5 b6 { The clever tactical point! If White moves the rook to b5 then we will play 21...a6. Therefore, White has to sacrifice material. } 
21. Bxg7 bxc5 
22. Bf6 { This endgame is equal, though of course a lot of precision is required from both sides. } Rd6 
23. Be7 Ra6 
24. Rxc5 Rxa2 
25. d5 f6! { Black is willing to forfeit the f-pawn in order to bring the king into the game and stop the d-pawn from promoting. With best play, the endgame will be drawn.

White has many options from here and it is beyond the scope of the course to analyze this endgame exhaustively. I would recommend ambitious students to investigate this position independently, with the help of a strong engine.

This type of exercise is recommended from time to time in the course as it is very beneficial to analyze the kind of middlegames and endgames that may arise from your opening choices. } 
