6. cxd5 { This is the main idea in this variation of the Grünfeld.

White voluntarily gives up the bishop pair while temporarily grabbing a pawn. Black will soon restore material, but White will have fixed the pawn structure in a particular way (obtaining the so-called 'Carlsbad structure'), and they are banking on this being to their advantage. } Nxg5 {[%mdl 32768]} { Capturing the bishop on g5 and remaining down a pawn for now is best, as Black has a concrete way of restoring material equality soon. } 
7. Nxg5 e6 { The double attack on g5 and d5 allows Black to recover the pawn. } 
8. Qd2 h6! ( { White's idea with this move is that if we play } 8...exd5 { , they will play } 9.Qe3+ { and force our king to move to f8. This is playable, but we have another way of continuing that I think is even simpler. } ) 
9. Nh3 { Sometimes White drops the knight to h3, with the intention to move it to f4 and pressure d5 from there. } exd5 
10. Nf4 O-O! { The pawn on d5 is not concerning, because if White captures it then we will play 11...c6 and capture on d4 next.

The exchange of these pawns and consequent opening up of the position would benefit us as the side with the bishop pair. } 
