6. cxd5 { This is the main idea in this variation of the Grünfeld.

White voluntarily gives up the bishop pair while temporarily grabbing a pawn. Black will soon restore material, but White will have fixed the pawn structure in a particular way (obtaining the so-called 'Carlsbad structure'), and they are banking on this being to their advantage. } Nxg5 { Capturing the bishop on g5 and remaining down a pawn for now is best, as Black has a concrete way of restoring material equality soon. } 
7. Nxg5 e6 { The double attack on g5 and d5 allows Black to recover the pawn. } 
8. Nf3 exd5 
9. b4 { This is the same idea that we saw in the variation beginning with 8.Qd2 when we examined such a position after White played 11.b4.

Since the play here is of a flexible character, it is not constructive to try to think in terms of specific move sequences. For this reason, the plan we will show here is informational only. } O-O 
10. e3 Be6 
11. Be2 Qe7 { Targeting the b4-pawn. } 
12. Qb3 Nd7 
13. O-O c6 { The usual setup is complete: bishop on e6 supporting d5. Queen either on e7 or d6 connecting rooks and targeting the b4 pawn. Pawn on c6 connecting the pawn chain and preparing to push our b-pawn if allowed. } 
14. Rac1 ( 14.b5 Rfc8 { It's not a big deal if White lands on b5 first. Especially with the queen on b3, the opening of the b-file after } 15.bxc6 bxc6 { would be in Black's favor. Also, we can now more easily push our pawn to c5 in the future, which would give us some hope to bring our dark-squared bishop to life on the long diagonal. } ) b5! {[%mdl 32768]} 
