One key strategic point to keep in mind is that let's say White places a knight on c5 and we place ours on c4. Then we maneuver our dark-squared bishop to f8 and threaten to take the White knight. In this case, if we do so White will not gain a passed pawn.

However, if White takes our knight on c4 with any piece, then we will immediately gain a protected passed pawn. This is one of the reasons why a knight on c4 gives such trouble to White. } 
