18. e4 { White has many paths forward in this complex middlegame, but we will quickly examine what strikes me as the most natural continuation. } Be6 
19. d5 Bg8 
20. a4 { White seeks to undermine Black's queenside. } Nxa4 
21. Nxa4 bxa4 
22. e6 { This looks like the scariest continuation, locking our light-squared bishop out of the game indefinitely. } Qd6! 
23. Qxa4 Rfb8 {[%cal Gf6f5,Gc7c6]} { Black will play 24...f5 next and will try to break the d5 pawn by playing ...c6 in the near future.

In my view, this position is deceptive in that it feels like Black is getting squeezed but I think it is in fact White that has to play strong moves in order to avoid a collapse of their fragile center and queenside.

Black's active pieces coupled with the bishop pair are a tough force to tame! } 
