On the other hand, Black has well-placed pieces targeting the center and queenside. If White's b-pawn were to fall, Black's pawn on a6 can become very dangerous in later stages of the game.

The position is equal although very complex. Students who have additional time are encouraged to study such positions in more depth by themselves, in order to gain a deeper understanding of the middlegame.

In summary, the Russian System is one of the most challenging systems to face from the Black side which has led to many strong Grandmasters employing it over the last few decades. The good news is that it leads to very sharp positions with chances for both sides, which is about as much as we can hope for as Grünfeld players! } )
