3. Nc3 d5 
4. cxd5 ( { This move marks the beginning of the Exchange Variation.

The study of the Grünfeld can be broadly divided into two sections. The first part is when White maintains the tension in the center. The second part is when White plays } 4.cxd5 { entering the so-called Exchange Variation. This is the most popular move and leads to many challenging variations. Traditionally, it has been seen as the most ambitious approach that White can take against the Grünfeld.

Strategically speaking, the Exchange Variation is premised on the idea that White's best bet is to establish an imposing center as quickly as possible. Black has to play } 4...Nxd5 { here and White's idea is to follow up with } 5.e4 { .

That said, White has other possibilities as early as the fifth move, which is what we will be studying in this chapter. } ) Nxd5 {[%mdl 32768]} 
5. Nxd5?! Qxd5 
6. e3 { White's intention is to bring the king's knight via e2 to c3 and gain time on Black's queen. } c5 
7. Ne2 ( 7.Nf3? { is the most popular move online, but it only serves to gift Black an easy game after } 7...Bg7 { and 8...Nc6. White will have no good way of dealing with the pressure against d4. } ) cxd4 
8. Nc3 { This is White's big idea, but if we know how to respond correctly we can secure at least equality. } Qe5 { An important square. The point is that White cannot recapture with the e-pawn. } 
9. Qxd4 Qxd4 
10. exd4 { Exchanging queens is good for us on strategic grounds, since White has the worse pawn structure. } Bg7 
11. Nd5 { This is the only really challenging move, as White threatens to play 12.Nc7+. } Kd8 
12. Bf4 { White renews the threat. } Nc6 
13. Nc7? ( { After } 13.Bc7+ Ke8 14.Bg3 Kd8 { White will have nothing better than to force a draw. } ) e5! {[%cal Gc7a8,Ge5f4,Gd8c7][%csl Ra8,Rf4,Rc7]} { White is losing here as Black will first grab the f4-bishop and in a few moves corral the stranded knight on a8, emerging with two minor pieces for a rook. } 
