4. cxd5 ( { This move marks the beginning of the Exchange Variation.

The study of the Grünfeld can be broadly divided into two sections. The first part is when White maintains the tension in the center. The second part is when White plays } 4.cxd5 { entering the so-called Exchange Variation. This is the most popular move and leads to many challenging variations. Traditionally, it has been seen as the most ambitious approach that White can take against the Grünfeld.

Strategically speaking, the Exchange Variation is premised on the idea that White's best bet is to establish an imposing center as quickly as possible. Black has to play } 4...Nxd5 { here and White's idea is to follow up with } 5.e4 { . } ) Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Qa4+ Nd7 ( { White's claim with this check is that Black does not have any ideal way to block it. } 7...c6 { is not desirable because in the Grünfeld we want to break White's center by pushing the pawn to c5 directly.

} ) ( 7...Bd7 { forces White to spend another tempo with their queen, but as it turns out the queen is happy to drop back to a3 from where it covers the c5-square.

} ) ( 7...Nd7 { has the drawback that we usually wish to play our knight out to c6 in order to pressure the d4-pawn. So, which is the lesser evil?! } ) ( { In fact other moves, such as } 7...c6 { or } ) ( 7...Qd7 { are also playable. However, I like this approach as it turns out that our knight from d7 can serve various useful functions.

Firstly, it can support the c5-pawn push. Secondly, it can shift to b6 and target the White queen as well as the c4-square. Finally, in some lines, we can move the knight to f6 and immediately put White's pawn on e4 en prise. } ) 
8. Nf3 O-O 
9. Bg5 { This is an aggressive move designed to make it difficult for Black to complete their development in harmonious fashion. } c5 
