11. Bd3 ( { Black sidesteps the x-ray along the d-file and exploits the fact that White cannot play } 11.Bxe7 { because after } 11...Re8 { the pawn on e4 would fall when White moves the bishop. } ) a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} { Threatening 12...b5. } 
12. Qa3 e5 ( { Stopping the threat, since now after } 12...b5 13.Bxb5 { there is no longer the intermezzo move } 13...Nb6 { hitting the queen on a4 and defending the rook on a8 simultaneously. } ) 
13. O-O Re8 
14. d5 c4 
15. Bc2 Bf8 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gf8d6,Gf7f6]} { Black will set themselves up with the moves 16...b5, 17...Bd6 and 18...f6 (although perhaps the order may be inverted depending on what White does).

Both sides have a threatening pawn structure, with White having a protected passed pawn while Black has a queenside pawn majority. That said, White's d5-pawn will be well-blockaded so I believe Black has the better practical chances to cause problems by pushing the a- and b-pawns. } 
