} ) ( 7...Nd7 { has the drawback that we usually wish to play our knight out to c6 in order to pressure the d4-pawn. So, which is the lesser evil?! } ) ( { In fact other moves, such as } 7...c6 { or } ) ( 7...Qd7 { are also playable. However, I like this approach as it turns out that our knight from d7 can serve various useful functions.

Firstly, it can support the c5-pawn push. Secondly, it can shift to b6 and target the White queen as well as the c4-square. Finally, in some lines, we can move the knight to f6 and immediately put White's pawn on e4 en prise. } ) 
8. Nf3 O-O 
9. Be2 { This quiet developing move is the main line. White is careful to avoid further delays of kingside castling. } Nb6!? ( { At first, I wanted to recommend } 9...c5 { . However, the theory gets incredibly complicated. You can take a look at the game Magnus Carlsen - Ian Nepomniachtchi from the Sinquefield Cup 2019 as an example of the devilish waters Black must enter in order to equalize.

Our move is the other playable option in the position but it is much rarer, so hopefully, we can benefit from the element of surprise against a lot of opponents. } ) 
10. Qa3 Qd6 
11. O-O Be6 { This is Black's strong idea. We are trying to exploit the weak c4-square. } 
12. Re1 { This was the choice of GM Nihal Sarin, one of the rising stars of Indian chess. } Qxa3 {[%mdl 32768]} 
13. Bxa3 Rfe8 { Defending the e7-pawn. } 
14. Nd2 { White guards the c4-square from invasion. } c6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gc6c5,Ge7e5]} ( { Black had obtained a simple and completely equal middlegame in Nihal-Chigaev 2019.

Over the coming moves Black can seek to prepare a pawn break with either ...f5, ...e5, or ...c5 all being possible depending on what White does.

If you want a more aggressive continuation you can also study } 14...c5!? { which we will examine in the next variation. [/variation/22124281/#/14/b] } ) 
