8. Rc1 ( { This is the most popular sideline. With the c3-pawn defended, White is ready to play 9.d5 if allowed.

Note that } 8.Nf3 { is covered in the next chapter and } ) ( 8.Bc4 { is not scary. We can play } 8...Nc6 9.Ne2 O-O { taking us to a position covered in the 7.Bc4 exchange variation, while if you wish you can also play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/6p1/2p5/3PP3/2P1B3/P4PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq c6 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8.Bc4 Qa5 aiming for a queenless middle game very similar to the one covered here in the 8.Rc1 line but where White has played the less useful move 8.Bc4. } ) Qa5! { The threat is ...cxd4 when White cannot, for now, recapture with the c-pawn. This also prevents 9.d5 as the c3-pawn would be en prise. } 
9. Qd2 cxd4 
10. cxd4 Qxd2+ 
11. Kxd2 O-O 
12. Nf3 Nc6 
13. d5 Rd8! { For now, we do not have to move our knight, while the threat of 14...e6 means that White generally steps the king away from the d-file. } 
14. Ke1 ( { This is the safer retreat versus } 14.Kc2 { . However, it does have the drawback that White's rook on h1 will take a much longer time to get into the game. } ) ( 14.Bd3? Nb4 { is unpleasant for White as we are threatening both 15...Nxd3 and 15...e6. } ) Na5 {[%mdl 32768]} { Black controls the c4-square, which is useful as it robs White of the possibility of 15.Bc4. If White plays a passive move here, we will break with 15...f5. } 
15. Bg5 ( 15.Bf4 { This move looks scary, but the threat can be easily parried. } { Bd7 This is the best way of stopping the threat of 16.Bc7 as now we can meet it with 16...Rdc8 and the knight on a5 cannot be captured as the rook on c1 will be lost. } ) Bd7 
16. Bd3 ( 16.Bxe7 Re8 17.d6 Nc6 { would make life very easy for us, so White makes sure to defend the e4-pawn to create the threat of 17.Bxe7. } ) f5 { Active play is best here once again. This makes sense since opening up the position should be to our advantage given that White's piece coordination is not ideal because of the time wasted moving their king around. } 
17. Bxe7 { We need to check the consequences of White winning a pawn, especially since with this move White leaves themselves with a passed d-pawn. } Re8 
18. d6 fxe4 
19. Bxe4 Bc6 
20. Ng5 ( { The simplest solution. Black is not concerned with } 20.Bxc6 { as after } 20...Nxc6 { the e7-bishop falls and we quickly recover our pawn. } ) Bf8 { White cannot hang onto the extra pawn as the pressure along the e-file is too great. } 
21. f3 { White's best bet is to fortify on e4 and claim a miniscule advantage in the resulting simplified middlegame. } Bxe7 
22. dxe7 Rxe7 
23. Kf2 h6 
24. Bxc6 Nxc6 { I think it's a little easier to play this position as White in practical terms, because their position is a little more compact. That said, the objective evaluation is complete equality. } 
