8. Nf3 ( { Much like in the previous chapter, against the main line of } 8.Nf3 { we will once again seek out an early queen exchange and then set out to prove that White has no major advantage in the resulting simplified middlegame. } { We will explore several of White’s tries after we reach the critical position after @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1p3pbp/p1n1p1p1/8/3PP3/3BBN2/P2K1PPP/2R4R b kq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@ 14...O-O . In spite of White’s ample choice, there is not much possibility for them to press for an advantage as Black’s position proves to be solid against all of White’s serious tries ( 15.Rc4 , 15.h4 as well as 15.Rc5 ).

Black’s strategy is similar against all of White’s options, namely we will try to fight along the open c-file to generate piece activity and, in some cases, to reduce the amount of material on the board. If we are successful, we will quickly kill off any of White’s pressure against our position, while the presence of a queenside pawn majority for Black does mean that we may be able to fight for the win in the later stages of the game. } ) *

