[Event "My First Grünfeld Opening Repertoire"]
[White "17) Exchange Variation - The Classical Variation"]
[Black "Chapter 17) Exchange Variation - The Classical Variation"]
[Date "2023.02.07"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D85"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23142009"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { The Classical Variation concludes our study of the Grünfeld, and it is a fitting end to the course as it remains one of the most aggressive and challenging systems that White can throw at us.

A key idea behind this system is the development of White’s kingside knight to e2 instead of f3, with the benefit being that now Black does not have the usual idea of playing ...Bg4 pinning the white knight since with the knight on e2, White can block the pin by playing the move f2-f3. As a result, we will study an alternative way of developing our light-squared bishop, eventually fianchettoing it with the move 10...b6 [/variation/22490742/#/10/b].

The main line will once again showcase a typical plan by Black, involving reducing the influence of White’s greater central control by opening up the c-file and seeking out heavy-piece exchanges. By playing in this way Black makes sure to avoid being overwhelmed by a forceful White kingside attack, which is a common occurrence in the Exchange Variation of the Grünfeld due to the strength of White’s central control. } *

