1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 
4. cxd5 ( { This move marks the beginning of the Exchange Variation.

The study of the Grünfeld can be broadly divided into two sections. The first part is when White maintains the tension in the center. The second part is when White plays } 4.cxd5 { entering the so-called Exchange Variation. This is the most popular move and leads to many challenging variations. Traditionally, it has been seen as the most ambitious approach that White can take against the Grünfeld.

Strategically speaking, the Exchange Variation is premised on the idea that White's best bet is to establish an imposing center as quickly as possible. Black has to play } 4...Nxd5 { here and White's idea is to follow up with } 5.e4 { . } ) Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { This is the most popular of White's seventh move options. White is choosing to develop the bishop first in order to follow up with 8.Ne2.

By avoiding placing the king's knight on f3, White stops Black from any problematic pinning of the knight (and consequent undermining of the center) that often happens after Black plays the light-squared bishop to g4. } c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 
8. Ne2 O-O ( { By castling first, we avoid some complicated lines after } 8...Nc6 9.d5!? ) 
9. h4 { This is a rare try, but it's been played by none other than Magnus Carlsen himself, so we should take it seriously!

The idea is quite typical in the Grünfeld, where Black's pawn on g6 provides a fast target. Since White has not yet committed to castling, they expect to place their king on } { f1 where it will be relatively safe. How to combat this plan?!

Note that 9.O-O will transpose after 9...Nc6 10.Be3 . } cxd4 
10. cxd4 Nc6 { Following the principle that a kingside attack may often best be countered by a central counter-attack, a principle that applies to many Grünfeld positions. } 
11. Be3 Na5 { A clever trick to combat this line! If White loses their light-squared bishop then their kingside attack will be a lot easier to parry. } 
12. Bd3 Nc6 ( { If you wish to avoid a possible repetition, you can investigate the somewhat risky alternative of } 12...h5!? ) { Now we attack the pawn on d4 again. } 
13. Bc2 Qa5+ {[%cal Gf8d8,Gc6d4,Gg7d4,Gd8d4][%csl Rd4]} 
{ The plan for Black is to put further pressure on the center after  14.Kf1  with  14...Rd8  . White has given up too much coordination to launch an attack and it is Black who has the better chances in the ensuing middlegame.

    Objectively speaking White's best move is  14.Qd2  but after  14...Qxd2+ 15.Kxd2 15...Rd8  it's hard for White to defend the   d4 pawn. }
