35. Bg2 { With his last two moves, Black has forced first the knight on d6 to move away from covering the c4-square and then the bishop from f1 to move to g2. As a result, the c4-square is now wide open. } Nc4! { Incredibly resilient play from Nepomniachtchi, and now Mamedyarov is the player who must be careful to avoid defeat. The current threat is 36...Bxf5 followed by 37...Rxg2+ and 38...Ne3+, winning a piece. } 
36. Ne3? { Under big pressure, Mamedyarov stumbles. } Bh3! { White is lost. The threat is to play 37...Nxe3 followed by winning the bishop on g2. } 
37. Kg1 Nxe3 { Unfortunately for White, the minor piece endgame is completely lost. } 
38. Rc5+ ( 38.Kxh2 Nxc2 39.Bxh3 Nxa3 { The queenside pawns are unstoppable. } ) Kd4 
39. Kxh2 Bxg2 
40. Rxg5 { White had nothing better than to seek out this endgame, but the rook is no match for the bishop and knight coupled with Black's queenside pawn majority.

The rest of the moves require no commentary, as Nepomniachtchi converts the endgame. } Bxf3 
41. Rg6 a5 
42. Rg5 Ng4+ 
43. Kg1 Ne5 
44. Kf2 Bxe4 
45. Ke2 b4 
46. axb4 axb4 
47. Rg8 Bd3+ 
48. Kd1 b3 
49. Rb8 Kc3 
50. g4 b2 { Mamedyarov resigned here, not wishing to test Nepomniachtchi's ability to checkmate with bishop and knight! I like this game as it demonstrated a very principled response to the aggressive 5.h4-line.

Then, it showed how alert the Grünfeld player should always be, since an almost imperceptible inaccuracy in the middlegame suddenly allowed White to take full control of the game, winning a pawn and establishing a huge advantage.

However, Nepomniachtchi digs deep and maintains as solid a position as possible. Mamedyarov then stumbles at the critical moment and after that Black is able to reestablish active pieces, leading to an opportunity to win material by tactical means and ultimately deciding the game. } 
