16. Ke2 {[%cal Gd4d5]} { White steps the king away from the d-file and hints at the possibility of advancing in the center. } Rfc8 { Black invites the advance of the d-pawn. Better was 16...Na5, but perhaps Aronian as the much higher-rated player wanted to invite complications. } ( 16...Na5! { appears to have been best. The threat is to play 17...Nxc4 followed by 18...Bb5, so White must conserve the bishop. } 17.Bd3 Rfc8 { Unlike in the game, the advance here } 18.d5?! { has no sting, due to } 18...exd5 19.exd5 b5 { threatening 20...Nc4. } 20.Nd2 Nb7 { Black eyes up both the d6 and c5-square.

The position is about equal but feels easier to play for Black as they are the side that can make improving moves in the short term. e.g. advance the f-pawn, improve the knight, exchange rooks along the c-file, bring the king closer to the center, etc. } ) 
17. d5 { White makes the right decision and breaks in the center at the right time. Nevertheless, Black has enough resources to deal with the advance. } exd5 
