} ) ( 19.Rb1! { was most precise, causing somewhat uncomfortable pressure against Black's queenside. Nevertheless, Black can hold here but it would require some precise play. } 19...b5 20.Rbc1 { Having provoked the advance of the b-pawn, White refocuses the efforts against the now weakened c6-knight. } 20...a5 { Black advances the pawns, forcing White to find a way of adding further pressure to the queenside. } { 20...Rab8? Rushing to play this move would lead to tactical trouble. 21.Bf4! Rb6 22.e5 Threatening the destructive 23.e6. Black is tangled up and has no good way to meet White's threat. } 21.Rd2 { White prepares 22.Rdc2, but leaves the c1-rook undefended in the process. } 21...Rab8! 22.Bf4 { Before, Black could not play this move because there was no good response to 22.Bf4. However, here Black has a nice idea. } 22...Nb4! 23.Rxc8 Rxc8 24.Bb7 Rc2! { Black solves the problems on the queenside through the use of short tactical lines.

This is an extremely important skill to have in chess generally, but it is especially important to develop it as a Grünfeld player since it is often the case that you will have to spot such 2-3 move tactics in order to resolve opening pressure or to seize the advantage against imprecise play from your opponent. } ) Nb4! { Black offers up the b7-pawn, but as it turns out White has no perfect way of capturing. With this move Black has already equalized, and the pressure will be on White to prove the draw as we shall soon see. } 
20. Bxb7 ( 20.Rxc8 { This was White's safest way of playing for a draw. } 20...Rxc8 21.Bxb7 Rb8 22.Bd5 Bb5 { Threatening 23...Bc3+. } 23.Rb1 Nxd5 24.exd5 Rd8 { Black will recover the pawn next, and if White is not careful they will face some pressure against the bishop pair. } 25.Nd4! Rxd5 26.Nxb5 axb5 { With simple equality. } ) Rxc1 
21. Rxc1 ( 21.Bxc1? { This move is a good illustration of the poisonous dynamic nature of the Grünfeld. Suddenly Black is completely winning. } 21...Rb8 22.Bd5 Bb5 { White is up a pawn but his position is, somewhat surprisingly, resignable. The reason is that his king is too weak and cannot combat the multiple threats of 23...Nd3, 23...Bc3+ and even 23...Rc8. } ) Nd3+ 
22. Kd2 Nxc1 
23. Bxa8 Nxa2 { This tactical sequence is what Aronian had calculated. The position is drawn, but as is often the case in the Grünfeld, Black is the one with the better practical chances owing to the outside passed pawn. } 
24. Nd4 a5 
25. Nc6 Bf8 
26. Bd4 { White improves his pieces, but has missed an important opportunity to eliminate the a-pawn from the board. } ( 26.Nxa5! { White no doubt missed this clever tactic in order to force the draw. } 26...Bb4+ { At first it seems as though Black is just winning a piece. } 27.Kc2 Bxa5 28.Kb3! Nc3 { 28...Nb4 29.Bd2 Nc6 30.Bxc6 Bxc6 31.Bxa5 Bxe4 With a draw. } 29.Bd2 Ba4+ 30.Kc4 Bb5+ 31.Kb3 { Black can force a perpetual, but he cannot escape the pin. A very clever idea for the white side! } ) a4 
