29. h3 h4! {[%cal Ge8b5,Gb5f1,Gf1h3]} { A clever idea, now Black has locked the h-pawn and forces White to keep in mind the possibility of a quick attack against this pawn in the future. Black also sets a very sneaky trap by leaving their pawn on h4 vulnerable to a quick capture. } 
30. Bf6? { White takes the bait. } Bxc6 ( 30...Bg7! { Immediately bringing the bishop to g7 was more precise, winning on the spot. } 31.Bxg7 Kxg7 { Black threatens 32...Bxc6 next, followed by 33...Nb4 and 34...a2. } 32.Nd4 Nb4 33.Kc3 a2 34.Kb2 { 34.Nb3 Ba4 35.Na1 Nc2 36.Kb2 Nxa1 37.Kxa1 Bb5 and the h3-pawn will soon fall, and with it, the game will be lost. In my opinion, these variations show the depth of understanding and practical playing strength of a world-class player like Aronian as he created all these practical opportunities with the clever move 28...h5! } 34...Nd3+ 35.Kxa2 Nxf4 { With a winning endgame. } ) 
31. Bxc6 Nb4 
32. Bb5 Bg7 
33. Bxg7 Kxg7 { White has an extremely unpleasant defensive task ahead, but with perfect play may be able to hold. } 
34. Kc3 g5! {[%cal Gf4f5,Gg7f6,Gf6e5,Gc3b4,Ga3a2]} { A thematic move, breaking apart White's pawn control in order for the Black king to invade. } 
35. fxg5 Kg6 
36. Bc4? { After constant pressure, White stumbles. } ( 36.Kb3! { White had one last chance to hold the balance, with this move. } 36...a2 37.Kb2 Kxg5 38.e5! { This was the very narrow path to equality. } 38...Kf4 39.Bc4! { White manages to grab the critical f-pawn just in time. } 39...Kxe5 40.Bxf7 Kf4 41.Bc4 Kg3 42.g5 Kxh3 43.g6 Nc6 { Black has to abandon the defense of the a-pawn in order to control White's advances, leaving a simple draw on the board. } ) Nc6! { A beautiful move. Black is able to reroute the knight into the center of the board from where it will devastate the White position. } 
37. Bd5 ( 37.Kb3? Na5+! { The key tactical idea. White loses the bishop as otherwise the a-pawn promotes. } ) Ne5 
38. Kb3 Nd3! { Black is focused on the h3-pawn. } 
39. Kxa3 Nf4 
40. Kb4 Nxh3 
41. e5 { Whtie opens the diagonal of the bishop in order to control the h1-square. } Nf4 
42. Be4+ Kxg5 
