45. Bb7 h3 
46. Bh1 ( 46.Ke7 { White cannot even try to grab the f-pawn. } 46...Kxe5 47.Kxf7 Nd8+! { , or } { 47...Ng5+ followed by 48...Ne4 also works. } ) Ng5 { Black will capture the g4-pawn next. } 
47. Kd5 Kxg4 
48. Kd4 Kf4 
49. Kd5 Ke3 
50. Kd6 -- ( { White appears to have either resigned here or lost on time. Black has several ways to win here, but the cleanest seems to me to be } 50...Kd4 { which will win the e-pawn as the only other option for White is to move their light-squared bishop. However, doing so will allow 51...Ne4+ after which the h-pawn will soon promote.

This game is instructive as it is a good demonstration of two important aspects of Grünfeld play:

1) The power of spotting short tactical patterns (2-4 moves) in order to solve opening problems or profit from the opponent's mistakes.

2) The practical winning chances that can come from having a queenside pawn majority. } )
