32. Qc1 Qd6 
33. Qc8 { White continues to try to generate winning chances, with her last move containing the dual threats of 34.a6 and 34.Qh8. } Rd1? { Against the pressure, GM Paravyan makes a significant mistake. The endgame that Black should seek is either Q+R+P or R+P, but not Q+P as you may easily land into a position where the White queen escorts the a-pawn to the promotion square while at the same time covering enough of the kingside squares to prevent perpetual checks. } ( 33...Qb4! 34.Ra1 { 34.Qe6+ Perhaps this was the move that concerned Black. 34...Kf8 35.a6 Ra3! 36.Rc1 For a human, such a position can feel very scary as White seems close to checkmating the weakened Black king. However, this is not the case. 36...Qd6 37.Rc8+ Kg7 38.Qg8+ Kh6 39.Qf8+ Kh5 Incredibly, the Black king is perfectly safe here! White is in fact the one under threat of checkmate as 40...Ra1+ is threatened. 40.Rc1 Qd2 41.Rf1 White is pushed into going passive. 41...Qe2 Everything is under control for Black. The a-pawn will fall next, while if White moves the rook away from f1 to generate threats against the Black king then Black can bring their rook to a2 and create mating threats of their own. } 34...Qd4 { The threat on the rook on a1 coupled with the possibility of 35...Rd2 (with pressure against f2) would have killed off any realistic chances of White advancing the a-pawn. } ) 
