39. Qa2 Qa7 
40. Kg1 Kc6 
41. Qf7 Qxa6 
42. Qxh7 { Black must have been feeling a strong sense of deja vu, as the inability to defend d6 and g6 means that Black will once again have to defend a pawn down. } Qd3? ( 42...Kd6 { Defending the e7-pawn was the correct play, as Black will be able to put enough pressure against f2 to make it impossible for White to convert the h-pawn. However, it is very easy to draw such conclusions from the comfort of one's home and with the support of a modern chess engine. It's a very different matter to find the best path at every turn when under pressure for the last twenty moves. } ) 
43. Qxe7 { White is once again winning, as Black's kingside pawns are too weak. } Qd1+ 
44. Kg2 Qd5+ 
45. Kf1 Qd1+ 
46. Qe1 Qd3+ 
47. Qe2 Qb1+ 
48. Kg2 Kd6 
