50. Qe3?! ( 50.g4! { This was the winning move. It's a testament to the devilishly tricky nature of Q+P endgames that two very strong and classically trained Russian Grandmasters both err on multiple occasions. A subtle point is that Black already has the pieces as well placed as they can be, so any move here will not help their defense. } 50...Kd6 51.h5 gxh5 52.gxh5 Kd7 53.Qe3 Kd6 54.h6 Qh7 55.Kh3 Qf5+ 56.Kh2 Qh5+ 57.Qh3 Qc5 58.Qh4 { The checks have run out, and White's pawn will soon promote. } ) Qc2 
51. g4 Qc4 
52. Kg3?! ( 52.Kf3! { White misses her last chance. This was the only winning move. The reason is extremely subtle. } 52...Qf1 53.Qd2+! { This is the point. With the king on f3 the Black king is between a rock and a hard place. If the king steps onto the e-file then 54. Qe2+ will force a winning pawn endgame. On the other hand, if the king steps onto the c-file then 54. Qc2+ will be played, followed by 55. Qxg6. An incredible detail. This endgame really has the feel of the kind of position that the famous chess trainer Mark Dvoretsky enjoyed analyzing in his advanced chess books. } ) Qd5 ( 52...Qf1 { This was even more precise, but the text move is enough for the draw. } ) 
53. f3 Qd6+ 
54. Kg2 Qd5 
55. Qf4 Qa2+ 
56. Kg3 Qa7! { A nice forcing solution ends the game. } 
57. Qxf6 Qg1+ 
58. Kf4 Qc1+ 
59. Ke4 Qe1+ 
60. Kd3 Qd1+ 
61. Kc4 Qa4+ 
62. Kd3 Qd1+ 
63. Ke4 { Draw, as White's king cannot avoid perpetual checks. An incredible fight from David Paravyan to save the game. At the same time, a beautifully instructive approach from Goryachkina who showed the challenges that even strong Grandmasters face when put under constant pressure from the get-go. } 1/2-1/2

